Coronavirus guidance is being updated.
Read what you can and cannot do

Namibia has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Namibia, see Return to the UK.
Travel
Namibia declared a state of emergency on 17 March and has closed its borders and ports to foreign nationals and non-residents entering the country. All commercial flights in and out of the country have been suspended.
Namibian nationals and permanent residents returning to Namibia from high-risk countries are required to enter supervised quarantine in a government facility for a period of 14 days.
If you need further information about entry requirements, contact the local immigration authorities or the nearest Namibia High Commission. You should also check with your airline or travel company for the latest information.
Local measures
Stage 2 of restrictions is in force for 28 days from 5 May to 1 June. These restrictions include:
All members of the public required to wear facemasks in public spaces
No restrictions on travel domestically within Namibia
Borders will remain closed
Certain businesses and activities are permitted to reopen – these include shopping malls and retail outlets, restaurants on a take away basis only
Buying and selling of alcohol is prohibited
Some activities considered high risk will not be permitted – e.g. theatres and cinemas, gyms and exercise centres, contact sports and sporting events, gambling houses and nightclubs, liquor stores and bars
Visas
British nationals currently in Namibia and unable to leave due to the restrictions on travel in response to coronavirus, should contact the Ministry of Home Affairs and Immigration in order to extend their entry stamp or visa.
Further information
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
